// Section 3: Methods and Tools

= Methods and Tools

Every method and tool used in this project is described below with its
historical basis. Where any deviation from strictly period practice occurs,
it is identified, described, justified, and compared to the period method.

== Tool Making

=== Shaping the Gravers

Each graver is shaped from a length of 3/16-inch (approximately 4.8 mm)
square A2 tool steel bar stock, cut to roughly 100–115 mm (4–4.5 inches).
The workflow is a hybrid of light forging and stock removal: the tang end
is first brought to a slight taper by hot working — heated to a forging
temperature and tapped down on the anvil over a few passes to start the
profile — and the rest of the shaping is then done cold, by grinding wheel,
files, and progressively finer abrasive papers. The cutting end is brought
to its square or lozenge cross-section and point geometry by stock removal,
and the forged tang taper is dressed and finished by file and abrasive
paper. Both halves of this workflow are documented period operations:
forging to start a tang taper is the universal approach to fitting tools
into burned-in handles, and Theophilus discusses files at length in Book
III of _De Diversis Artibus_, including the chapter "Of Files" already
quoted in §2.2 @theophilus-hendrie. The filed-and-fitted sequence
Theophilus describes in chapter XX (quoted in §3.1.2 below) names exactly
the operations used here: file the iron to shape, fit it into the handle,
then heat-treat. A modern French engraver documents an analogous workflow
— old file steel cut to length, heat-treated at 850°C, quenched in water,
and fitted to a lathe-turned wooden handle — demonstrating that the same
sequence remains the standard practitioner approach today
@engraverscafe-homemade.

=== Heat Treatment

The shaped blanks are hardened by heating to non-magnetic temperature
(approximately 1475°F / 800°C for plain carbon steels; higher for A2 due to
its alloy content) and air-cooling (A2) or quenching in oil or water
(O-1 / W-1). For A2 specifically, the austenitizing temperature is
approximately 1750–1800°F / 955–980°C; the steel is then cooled in still
air.
They are then tempered to a straw color to achieve approximately
Rockwell C 58–62. This hardness range allows the tool to hold a sharp edge
while cutting soft metals (copper, brass, silver) without being so brittle
that the tip chips readily. Period heat treatment used the same principles —
heating to critical temperature and quenching — with color judgment as the
primary means of gauging temperature, exactly as practiced here. Theophilus,
in Book III of _De Diversis Artibus_, gives the simplest possible recipe for
hardening the small cutting tools of the goldsmith's bench:

#quote(block: true)[
  Grooving irons are likewise tempered in this manner. When they have been
  filed and fitted in their handles, their end is placed in the fire, and
  presently, when it has begun to glow, it is taken out and quenched in
  water.
]

(Theophilus, _De Diversis Artibus_, Book III, ch. XX, "Of Tempering Iron,"
Hendrie translation @theophilus-hendrie.) The procedure described — heat
the working end to a glow, quench, then return to the fire briefly to draw
the temper — is the same operation performed in this project, with the
modern conveniences of a thermocouple and a tempering oven where Theophilus
and his contemporaries relied on color and experience @theophilus.
Ganoksin's guidance reflects the same logic: "gravers are sold in their
hardened state and any grinding should be done in such a way that this temper
is preserved. Touch the tool lightly to the grinding wheel, dipping it
frequently into water to prevent overheating. If the steel starts to show
color the temper has been compromised" @ganoksin-engraving-tools.

=== Sharpening Geometry

The cutting face is ground at 45° on the diagonal, with 15° heels (relief
bevels on the underside). For hand pushing specifically, a lower face angle
of 35–40° with a longer heel is preferred, as this geometry requires less
force and provides more control than the steeper angles used with modern
pneumatic tools. Sharpening is done on synthetic Japanese waterstones in a
1000 / 4000 / 8000 grit progression, followed by a leather strop dressed
with chromium-oxide compound (see §2.4). The face and heel surfaces must be flat and
polished to a mirror finish. The Antique Firearms Restoration Blog describes
the standard starting geometry: "the main face is cut at 45 degrees on the
diagonal and the heels are cut at 15 degrees. These angles can be varied
according to personal preferences, but 45/15 are a good starting point"
@cablesfarm-graver-sharpening. Experienced hand-push engravers recommend
lower face angles of 35–40° and longer heels for hand work
@engraverscafe-geometry.

=== Handle Turning and Tang Fitting

Handles are turned on a lathe from cherry (_Prunus_ sp.; see §2.3 for the
period justification) to the documented period mushroom-with-flat-bottom
shape. A small starter hole is drilled at a slight angle from the flat
face. The tang is then *burned into the handle*: the tapered end of the
tang is heated to a low red and pressed firmly into the starter hole. The
hot steel scorches the wood to the tang's exact profile, leaving carbonized
walls that grip the steel without slop and seat the shaft at the precise
angle the engraver wants. No ferrule, no set screw, no glue — the burned
fit alone holds the tool together for a working lifetime. Burning-in is the
traditional pre-modern method for fitting wooden handles to small steel
hand tools (chisels, gouges, files, awls, gravers); it produces a tighter
and more durable fit than a cold press into a precisely-drilled hole, and
it is the method Bosse's "bois ferme" criterion implicitly assumes — a
splitty wood would crack rather than scorch.

== Plate Preparation

The copper sheet is cut to size, hammered to working thickness if needed
(period plates were hammered, not rolled), and polished to a scratch-free
mirror finish. Period polishing was done progressively with finer abrasives
and burnishing. For this project, the plate is polished using progressively
finer grades of abrasive, finishing with a polishing compound — functionally
identical to period practice, though modern abrasive papers may be used in
place of period abrasive stones as a convenience substitution with no
functional difference.

== Design Preparation and Transfer

The source image is Moretto da Brescia's _The Conversion of Saint Paul_
(c. 1540–41), painted on a vault of the ambulatory of Santa Maria presso
San Celso in Milan, one of the sixteenth-century treatments of the subject
enumerated in the iconographic tradition discussed in §1.4
@moretto-conversion. The painting is studied and interpreted as a
line drawing. This is a creative act of translation —
the engraver must decide how to represent painted tonal values as line work
(hatching, cross-hatching, stippling). This process of converting paintings
into engraved line compositions was standard period practice; Marcantonio
Raimondi (c. 1480–1534) built his career on engraving reproductions of
Raphael's paintings. Lisa Pon's monograph _Raphael, Dürer, and Marcantonio
Raimondi: Copying and the Italian Renaissance Print_ documents the
systematic translation of Raphael's compositions into engraved reproductions
in Marcantonio's workshop, and treats this reproductive practice as central
to the formation of the sixteenth-century Italian print trade
@pon-raphael-marcantonio.

The line drawing is reversed (since the print will be a mirror image of the
plate) and transferred to the polished plate using lamp black on the back of
the drawing, traced with a steel stylus. Dürer is documented as having
worked from reversed preparatory drawings when planning his engravings;
Panofsky's biography discusses Dürer's preparatory practice in detail
@panofsky-durer.

== Engraving Technique

=== Grip and Cutting

The burin is held at approximately 30° to the plate surface. The mushroom
handle is cradled in the palm and the index and middle fingers guide the
shaft. Pressure is applied both downward and forward. The tool cuts into the
metal, forming a chip and pushing a thin curl of metal ahead of it. This is
push engraving — no hammer, no pneumatic assist, hand pressure only. Antony
Griffiths, in the standard British Museum handbook on prints and
printmaking, describes the same modern push-engraving grip and the basic
burin-and-chip mechanics that have remained unchanged from the fifteenth
century to the present @griffiths-prints.

=== Plate Rotation

The plate rests on a leather sandbag cushion and is rotated with the
non-cutting hand to produce curves. The cushion is the same simple device
that Abraham Bosse describes for his own workshop in 1645, in the chapter
on holding and managing the burin:

#quote(block: true)[
  And to this end you must make yourself a small cushion of fairly stout
  leather, somewhat in the shape of the pincushions that women and girls
  use to hold needles and pins, half a foot square in width and three or
  four inches in height, filled with rather fine sand; and you shall set
  this cushion upon a table firmly fixed in place. Then you shall lay your
  plate upon this cushion, so that you may turn it according as the lines
  and hatchings shall require.
]

(Translated from Bosse, _Traicté des manieres de graver en taille dovce
svr l'airin_, Paris, 1645, in the chapter "Briève maniere pour sçavoir
tenir, manier & aiguiser un Burin." Cited from the Duke University
Libraries copy digitized by the Internet Archive @bosse-traite.) A. Hyatt Mayor, in
_Prints and People_, observes that Schongauer was the first engraver to
curve parallel lines by rotating the plate against a steady burin
#cite(<mayor-prints-people>, supplement: [p. 130]) — a technique that, as
Bosse confirms two centuries
later, depends entirely on the sand-filled leather cushion holding the
plate steady but free to swing.
The Diderot Encyclopédie plates clearly illustrate the same arrangement
@diderot-encyclopedie.

=== Line Vocabulary

All tonal variation is achieved through line character and density. The
line vocabulary consists of: pure line (continuous clean strokes for
contours); hatching (parallel lines of varying spacing and depth for
shading); cross-hatching (crossed sets of parallel lines for deeper shadows,
pioneered by Schongauer and perfected by Dürer); and stippling (dots and
short flicks for texture, documented from the late 15th century). Wendy
Thompson describes Schongauer's technique: he "used a great variety of
strokes — from the long, sinuous lines that create the beard of the saint
and the curling fur of one of the demons, to the short flecks of the saint's
coarsely woven robe; he also made use of crosshatching in the deepest
shadows to model the forms" @met-thompson-engraving.

=== Workflow Sequence

The period engraving workflow, documented across multiple sources:

+ Design preparation;
+ Plate preparation and polishing;
+ Design transfer in reverse;
+ Contour engraving (main outlines first);
+ Shading (hatching, cross-hatching);
+ Textures and details (stippling, fine work);
+ Cleaning and finishing (removing burrs and metal curls);
+ Printing if desired (inking, wiping, pressing) @curtidoscabezas-burin.

== Deviations from Period Methods

The following deviations from strictly period practice are made in this
project, with justification:

/ A2 tool steel instead of period carbon steel: Justified by the engraver's
  existing familiarity with this material from prior toolmaking. The
  functional result (hardened steel graver at Rc 58–62) is identical. See
  §2.2 for full comparative analysis.

/ Synthetic Japanese waterstones for sharpening: Used in place of period
  European natural hones. The functional result (a mirror-polished face
  and heel on the burin, finished on a leather strop) is the same edge a
  period engraver would have produced. See §2.4 for full discussion.

/ Modern abrasive papers for plate polishing: Used as a convenience
  alongside traditional polishing methods. The functional result
  (mirror-polished copper surface) is identical to period preparation.
  Period engravers used progressively finer natural abrasive stones and
  burnishing to achieve the same result.

/ Electric lighting: Period engravers worked by natural light or candlelight.
  Modern lighting is used for practical reasons at indoor events. This has
  no effect on the object itself.

No pneumatic or power-assisted tools are used. No diamond or ceramic
sharpening equipment is used. No modern quick-change handle systems are
used. Aside from the substitutions enumerated above, the core operation —
pushing a hand-held steel burin into a polished copper plate to lift a
curl of metal — is unchanged from the period practice documented by
Theophilus, Bosse, and the surviving plates of Schongauer and Dürer.
